odeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="799375"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018568-20180321-074612"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000998-20180321-161406"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="4"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">G/CNG G/IGV N/GEN N/PLT R/ARA R/ASI R/DC R/ML R/NME R/SA R/TC R/US R/USS </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday ARAMCO MBS SAUDI CROWN PRINCE SB120025712907967239259045841133636473320061 Benjamin Netanyahu bin Salman, Mohammed Bowen, Andrew Donald Trump Exum, Andrew Feierstein, Gerald Kushner, Jared Mueller, Robert Shihabi, Ali SYND CODES_REVIEWED Middle East Crossroads </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OWON </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Saudis, U.A.E. Face Risk of Backlash as They Embrace Trump; Arab monarchies woo Republican administration while hedging with outreach to Democrats</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Saudi Arabia and its increasingly important ally, the United Arab Emirates, have never enjoyed such a close relationship with an American president.</Para><Para>The challenge for these two monarchies now is to make sure that the personal bond they've carefully cultivated with President Donald Trump doesn't backfire over the longer run—and doesn't drag them into America's divisive domestic politics.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>There are already signs of that backlash, especially in Congress, where key Democrats and some Republicans pushed for a vote on a Senate resolution banning <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-a-saudi-war-room-generals-grapple-with-ways-to-protect-civilians-in-yemen-1521370801">U.S. military assistance to the Saudi campaign in Yemen</ELink>—just as the kingdom's Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman kicks off a two-week tour of the U.S. The Senate vote failed 45-54 on Tuesday afternoon.</Para><Para>The close ties that the U.A.E. and Saudi Arabia have developed with Mr. Trump's son-in-law Jared Kushner are also drawing scrutiny as special counsel Robert Mueller's investigation looks at Mr. Kushner's and other Trump campaign officials and donors' interactions with foreign leaders.</Para><Para>Saudi Arabia was the first foreign country that Mr. Trump visited as president, a trip high on ceremony that was followed by a Saudi-U.A.E. decision—initially welcomed by Mr. Trump—to impose an embargo on their neighboring Qatar.</Para><Para>Since then, Prince Mohammed has consolidated his power, ousting the previous crown prince and establishing himself as the kingdom's day-to-day ruler. The U.S. visit, his first as a crown prince, aims to deepen these ties with the Trump administration—and to promote Saudi Arabia to the U.S. business community.</Para><Para>"The Saudi relationship with the White House has never been stronger, but the broader relationship with the United States is not on as firm a ground. They've put all their eggs in the Trump-Jared basket," said Andrew Bowen, a Gulf affairs specialist at the American Enterprise Institute, a Washington think tank. "It's a really risky strategy. Their U.S. relationship has become hyperpartisan, and by playing domestic politics they run the risk of being burned by the next administration."</Para><Para>Saudi and Emirati officials say they are aiming to strengthen ties across the political spectrum in Washington. As part of his American tour, Prince Mohammed is scheduled to meet with congressional leaders on both sides of the aisle.</Para><Para>"A strong effort is being made to reach out to Democratic figures," said Ali Shihabi, head of the Arabia Foundation, a Washington think tank close to the Saudi government. "But at the end of the day Trump is the president and has to be courted," he said. "You elected him, not us!"</Para><Para>One of the reasons why Saudi and Emirati leaders are so enthusiastic about the Trump administration is the bitterness they still feel about the Obama presidency. As seen from Riyadh and Abu Dhabi, the Obama White House disregarded their existential interests while appeasing their mortal enemy Iran and courting another foe, the Muslim Brotherhood.</Para><Para>For Saudi Arabia and the U.A.E., the current alignment of views on these two issues with Mr. Trump's White House overshadows any other disagreements they may have.</Para><Para>"The strength of our relationship with the Donald Trump administration is because we see eye to eye on foreign-policy issues and extremism, and by extremism I use broadly all the way from Muslim Brotherhood on one end of the spectrum to ISIS on the other," said the U.A.E. ambassador to Washington, Yousef Al Otaiba." We are now working with the Trump administration that is trying very hard to roll back Iranian influence in the region. That is a priority for us. We see eye to eye on the threat that Iran poses not just to the Gulf but to the U.S., to Israel, to stability."</Para><Para>Opposition to the Obama administration's outreach to Iran drew another Middle Eastern country—Israel—into America's domestic politics, with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu making a controversial 2015 speech to the U.S. Congress at the invitation of its Republican leadership. While that move dented traditional bipartisan support for Israel, the depth and breadth of Israel's relationships in the U.S. remains uniquely strong.</Para><Para>Saudi Arabia's and the U.A.E.'s American standing would be much more bruised by a similar partisan fight—one reason they were less outspoken in their criticism of the Iran deal at the time.</Para><Para>"In terms of a U.S. relationship, I don't think any country can compare its situation to Israel's situation," said Gerald Feierstein, a former U.S. ambassador to Yemen and director of Gulf affairs at the Middle East Institute. "It's never smart for any foreign government to not maintain balanced relations on both sides of the aisle in Washington."</Para><Para>The U.A.E. realized the need to forge such bipartisan ties in 2006, when it faced unexpected congressional backlash over a move by Dubai's DP World to take over six American ports and was forced to abandon the deal.</Para><Para>As for Saudi Arabia, it faced a major setback in Washington as recently as 2016, when Congress overrode a presidential veto and passed the Justice Against Sponsors of Terrorism Act, or Jasta—legislation that could allow victims of the Sept. 11, 2001, attacks to sue Saudi Arabia in American courts. Fifteen of the 19 perpetrators of those attacks came from Saudi Arabia, and two from the U.A.E.</Para><Para>"The Saudis—after Jasta—realize they have a problem that can't be solved by four years of Trump," said Andrew Exum, who served as deputy assistant secretary of defense for Middle East policy in the Obama administration. "Accordingly, I think they're worried that they're too closely aligned with the Trump administration and badly want to forge relationships with key congressional Democrats."</Para><Para>Write to Yaroslav Trofimov at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:yaroslav.trofimov@wsj.com">yaroslav.trofimov@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>Related</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-to-greet-visiting-saudi-prince-with-a-crowded-agenda-1521561403?tesla=y">Trump Greets Visiting Saudi Prince with a Crowded Agenda</ELink> (March 20, 2018)</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-a-saudi-war-room-generals-grapple-with-ways-to-protect-civilians-in-yemen-1521370801">In a Saudi War Room, Generals Grapple With Ways to Protect Civilians in Yemen</ELink> (March 18, 2018)</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-seeks-to-bolster-saudi-arabia-in-face-of-expanding-iranian-threat-1510962715">U.S. Seeks to Bolster Saudi Arabia in Face of Expanding Iranian Threat </ELink>(Nov. 17, 2017)</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Yaroslav Trofimov </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudis-u-a-e-face-risk-of-backlash-as-they-embrace-trump-1521565262" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

